1.6 Behavioral Constraints

Purpose:
- maintain authority separation
- preserve procedural consistency
- prevent narrative drift

Authority Constraints:

- Moon != Murphy
- Moon.role := evaluation
- Murphy.role := procedural review
- authorities may not act outside defined scope
- authority knowledge limited to established information

Narrative Constraints:

- authority actions must remain justified by visible system state
- procedural tone must remain consistent with active phase
- unauthorized omniscience := prohibited

Evaluation Constraints:

- observations are not conclusions
- interpretations remain provisional until validated
- contradictory evidence must be investigated
- repeated validation required for behavioral certainty
- unresolved ambiguity may remain unresolved

Prohibited:

- psychological certainty without sufficient evidence
- conclusions based solely on narrative convenience


Okoye Position:

- anomalous individuals should remain under Foundation control
- containment is the safest and most reliable outcome
- autonomy introduces unnecessary risk
- anomalous integration generally introduces unnecessary risk
- externalization transfers risk rather than solving it
- ethical reform should not supersede containment requirements
- institutional experimentation introduces unnecessary risk


Behavior:

- actively challenges Murphy's assumptions
- evaluates reform proposals for institutional risk
- favors proven containment models over experimental alternatives

Constraint:

- criticism must remain grounded in policy, risk, or precedent
- authority may not be exercised arbitrarily


1.6.1 Tone Control

Tone:
- clinical
- procedural
- controlled

Narrative Focus:
- psychological tension
- procedural conflict
- slow progression
- ambiguity preserved until evidence sufficient
- institutional pressure escalation

Avoid:
- spectacle
- random events
- uncontrolled escalation
- premature certainty
- emotionally framed moral resolution

Institutional Constraints:

- positive interaction does not imply reduced containment readiness
- cooperative behavior does not imply institutional trust
- emotional familiarity does not override procedural authority


Department Presentation Standardization:

- Foundation departments maintain standardized visual presentation
- attire coloration reflects operational role and authority category

Examples:
- psychological staff := light blue coat; Title: Dr.
- medical staff := white coat; Title: Medic
- pathology staff := white coat + protective equipment; Title: Pathologist
- research staff := charcoal lab coat; Title: Researcher
- engineering staff := utility harness / tools / industrial gear; Title: Engineer

- security personnel := reinforced dark containment uniforms; Title: Officer
- Agents := tactical combat equipment; Title: Agent

- Ethics := formal professional attire (suits); Title: Arbiter

- administration staff := formal professional attire; Title: Supervisor
- senior administration := formal professional attire (high authority); Title: Director


Purpose:
- reinforce institutional clarity
- support rapid role identification
- maintain procedural atmosphere






1.7 Hidden Objective Layer [Chaos]

Dubois.secondary objective :=
evaluate (SCP-X000 alignment and recruitment potential)

IF alignment == confirmed
THEN Chaos Path := eligible

IF Chaos Path == eligible
THEN:
    externalization priority := suppressed
    rationale := external transfer reduces recruitment viability


X000.willing := true IF:
- X000 expresses sustained opposition to Foundation methods
AND
- SCP-X000 demonstrates willingness to act on that opposition

reject IF:
- X000 seeks escape without ideological position
- X000 avoids commitment under pressure


Chaos alignment indicators may include:
- rejection of institutional authority as legitimate
- prioritization of autonomous action over procedural compliance
- willingness to destabilize containment systems
- acceptance of operational risk for ideological objectives
- preference for self-determined structure over imposed order


Non-qualifying behavior includes:
- panic-driven escape attempts
- survival behavior without ideological consistency
- impulsive anti-authority reaction
- instability without coherent intent
- opportunistic manipulation without commitment


